Gam models: summary

Research question

How did neonatal health evolve through time in Switzerland (2007-2020) ? Particularly, did it change during two important crisis: the 2008-2009 economic crisis and the current COVID-19 pandemic ?

We focus on the evolution of birthweight and gestational age, and on the rates of stillbirth, preterm birth, lowbirth weight and macrosomia babies.

Background on COVID-19:

  • COVID-19 infection among pregnant women : higher risk of severe symptoms (Kotlar et al., 2021; Villar et al., 2021).

  • Babies born from COVID+ mothers: increased rate of preterm births (Kotlar et al., 2021; McClymont et al., 2022; Villar et al., 2021).

  • pregnant women with comorbidities : higher risk of severe COVID-19, and important rates of stillborn and preterm neonates; ++ risk if infection during the third trimester (Vousden, 2022, UK study).

  • In Switzerland: maternal SARS-CoV-2 infection associated with increased incidence of low placental weight (Radan et al., 2022).

  • mental health among women worsened during COVID-19 : depression, stress and anxiety observed (Kotlar et al., 2021).

  • In Switzerland: increase in the rate of pregnant and breastfeeding women with depression and severe-anxiety-like symptoms (Lambelet et al., 2021, cross-sectionnal study).

Data and Methods

Data

We used data from the Federal Office of Statistics: Bevnat. It covers:

  • All births that occurred in Switzerland

  • Between 1987 and 2020 (year 2021 will soon be included)

  • Temporal level: monthly

  • Spatial level: Gemeinde nummer (municipality)

Variables

Socio economic and spatial variables

  • Swiss-SEP Average Swiss neighbourhood index of socioeconomic position (Swiss-SEP 2.0). Swiss-SEP 2.0 indicates the average socioeconomic situation in a municipality. It was developed by the Institute for Social and Preventive Medicine at the University of Bern.

  • Language region: German (+Romansh), French, Italian

  • Urbanicity of the place : Urban versus Rural

  • Grossregion, canton, districts

  • Gemeinde nummer/municipality

Exclusions steps

  • As gestational age was only recorded systematically from 2007, we analysed data from this year only
  • Steps of exclusions: see the ppt

Definitions:

  • Preterm birth babies : <37 weeks

  • Low birthweight babies : <2500g

  • Macrosomia babies: >= 4000g

  • “normal” birthweight babies: >2500 and <4000

We work with two different datasets:

  • one that includes stillbirth cases to investigate stillbirth outcome: bevn_eco_in6.

  • one that excludes stillbirth cases to investigate birthweight/gestational age/ preterm birth/ low birth weight/ macrosomia outcomes : bevn_eco_in7.

Characteristics at inclusion and in two other datasets used

  • see tables in html (folder: output/tables)

Methods

We built different GAM models, investigating the following outcomes:

  • birthweight as a continuous variable

  • stillbirth : binary yes/no variable

  • (gestational age: as a continuous variable, in days)

  • preterm birth: binary yes/no variable.

  • (low birthweight: binary yes/no variable, comparing LBW babies vs the rest)

  • low birthweight: binary yes/no variable, comparing LBW babies vs “normal” birthweight babies

  • macrosomia: binary yes/no variable, comparing macrosomia babies vs “normal” birthweight babies

In the models the variable “birth_Y_M_num” is used to account for time: it is numerical monthly time, with 1= January 2007 and 168=December 2020.

To take into account the fact that we are analysing a huge dataset (n=1,099,368), we calculated Cohen’s d. (calculation and interpreation of d guide

)

Cohen’s d formula:

\(d=\frac{beta}{SD}\) and \(SD=\sqrt{n}*se\)

\(d=\frac{beta}{\sqrt{n}*se}\)

  • beta: estimate
  • se: standard error
  • n: population/observation size
  • SD: standard deviation

Interpretation of m_BW_bam5_2 model :

  • Non-smooth terms

Increasing parity increases birthweight compared to first births: from (126g, 129g) at second parity, (171g, 176g) at third parity, to (195g, 204g) for parities over 3.

Being born a female decreases birthweight by (-148g, -146g) compared to males.

Urbanity seems to have no effect on birthweight (it is worth mentioning that it did have an effect as long as mean_ssep variable was not included in the model)

Language region : Compared to babies born in German(+Romansh)-speaking Switzerland, being born in the French-speaking part decreases BW by (-50g,-46g), while being born in the Italian-speaking part decreases BW by (-67g,-59g).

Maternal nationality: compared to babies born from Swiss mothers, babies born from Asian mothers are lighter (-22g, -14g). Babies born from other-nationalities mothers are heavier: (7g, 16g) for Africa, (31g, 34g) for other European countries, (55g, 75g) for Northern America, and (42g-53g) for Southern/Central America. –> What is the biological relevance of these changes? variations of around 50g probably don’t impact much neonatal health.

Interpretation of Cohen’s d parameters: we should not overinterpret these values. Usually it is considered that when d is<0.2, the effect should be considered very small. Here as all our ds are<0.2, it suggests that we may not see all these effects in much smaller datasets.

  • Smooth terms

Gestational age: Obviously, BW increases with increasing GA, with a plateau at around 800g for babies between 20 and 25 gestational weeks, and another plateau at around 4000g for babies above 45 weeks.

Maternal age: BW increases non-linearly with maternal age: for younger mothers (<25yo) it increases almost linearly from 3280g to 3340g, then declines very slightly until reaching a plateau around 3330g when the mother is 25-40yo. Older women have heavier babies, increasing from 3330g to around 3340g for women 40-50yo (keep in mind we have excluded a few mothers above 50).

Time (month+year combined): globally, BW is decreasing between 2007 and 2019 from 3350 to 3330 which is a minor change, and then increases from 2019 to reach 3350g by the end of 2020. There are some other minor variations throughout the whole time but this doesn’t seem very relevant: only 20g variation.

Seasonal/month: minor sinusoidal seasonal variation between 3330-3340g, with lower birthweight in March and August. These difference dont seem relevant either (10g variation will probably not impact the baby’s health).

Mean ssep: Birthweight increases by increasing ssep, linearly between ssep=25-45 approx (3250-3340g), and then there is some minor birthweight increase for higher ssep, until reaching a BW of around 3360g. Overall, a +100g increase is probably worth mentioning.

2008-2010

Because birth_Y_M_num and month variables correlated too much, month variable was not kept in the model. This was done in every “sub” model including only the years 2008-2010 or 2017-2020.

Mean ssep was set as linear variables (when included as a smooth, the graph clearly showed a linear association).

Time variables (birth_Y_M_num) and mean ssep variable were put as linear terms, because the model including them as smoothed terms showed that the relationship between these and stillbirth was linear.

Calculation of Cohen’s d for OR:

\(d= \log(OR) * \frac{\sqrt{3}}{\pi}\)

\(d = \frac{log(OR)}{1.81}\)

Comment:
- Gestational age has indeed a strong impact on stillbirth risk: the risk declines from 75% to 20% when the baby is born between 22 and 26 weeks. Afterwards, the risk declines to 15% when the baby is born at 31 weeks, and <5% after 35weeks.
- Maternal age: the risk is a bit reduced for women aged 25-35 years, compared to younger and older mothers, but stays at a very low level (0.15-0.16% compared to 0.13%)
- Month, seasonality : there seems to be an increased risk of stillbirth during summer >0.14% risk.

Non-smoothed variables:
- time (2007-2020), urbanicity ad SSEP seem to have no impact at all on stillbirth risk.
- language region: in French-speaking parts, there is a (borderline but non-significant) trend of having a increased risk of stillbirth compared to German-speaking parts.
- Maternal nationality: only babies born from African mothers seem to have an increase in stillbirth risk : OR 1.04-1.51.

Why we chose this model: Maternal age had edf values very close to one: we put it as a linear term instead of smoothed variable. As for the previous model (including all timing 2007-2020), we kept time (birth_Y_M_num) and mean_ssep2 variables as linear terms.

  • Time: apparently no effect

  • French speaking Switzerland: the increased risk of stillbirth persists.

  • Babies born from African mothers: the risk is furthermore increased compared to the whole timeline: OR 1.3-2.33

Comment:
- birthweight: Risk of preterm birth stabilizes when the baby gets at least 3.5kg. The risk increases again when the baby >6kg, but then the confidence interval gets wider due to smaller sample size.
- maternal age: risk declines from 1.8 to about 1.5% when the mother is young (<20 years old), then it is stabilized at 1.5% when the mother is 20-40years old, and increases again for older mothers (up to 3.5% for the older mothers). –> consistent with higher birthweight
- time : There is a marked decrease of preterm birth risk (change of definition??) from 1.6% in 2007, to around 1.35% in 2020.
- Month, seasonal: sinusoidal form, highest risks in June and December (1.4%-1.45%), lowest in March and September (1.35%) –> such small changes are probably not relevant.
- SSEP: clear increase in PTB risk when SSEP increases: risk at 1% for SSEP=24, up to a risk of 1.5% for SSEP of 87. –> consistent with higher birthweight when high SEP.

Non-smoothed terms:
- Parity: the risks increases as the parity increases, up to OR 1.4-1.6 for parities >3.
- Urbanity: babies born in rural areas have a slight reduction of the chance to be preterm. OR 0.93-0.97
- French and Italian-speaking parts: decreased risks, especially for Italian parts: OR 0.78-0.87
- Babies born from Asian or African mothers have less chance of being born before their term: OR 0.85-0.95 and OR 0.82-0.94, respectively.
Babies born from European (excl. Swiss) mothers and Southern/Central American mothers have on the contrary an increased of being preterm: OR 1.03-1.08 and OR 1.15-1.34, respectively.
